# 1. Business Goal Identification

## Definition

The first step in any ML project is understanding the business problem.

Machine learning should solve a real problem rather than being used simply because it is available.

## Examples

* Predict insurance costs
* Detect fraudulent transactions
* Recommend movies
* Recognize handwritten digits

## Output

A clearly defined business objective.

---

# 2. ML Problem Framing

## Definition

Convert the business problem into a machine learning problem.

## Examples

| Business Problem              | ML Problem Type        |
| ----------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Predict house prices          | Regression             |
| Detect spam emails            | Classification         |
| Group customers               | Clustering             |
| Teach an agent to play a game | Reinforcement Learning |

## Output

Selection of the correct ML approach.

---

# 3. Data Collection

## Definition

Gather data required for training the model.

## Sources

* CSV files
* Databases
* APIs
* Sensors
* User-generated data

## Example

For handwritten digit recognition:

Dataset = MNIST

Training Images = 60,000

Testing Images = 10,000

---

# 4. Data Preprocessing

## Definition

Cleaning and preparing raw data before training.

## Common Tasks

* Handling missing values
* Removing duplicates
* Fixing incorrect data types
* Handling outliers
* Normalization
* Standardization

## Example

Movie Recommendation Project:

* Removed duplicate movies
* Converted rating values to numeric
* Filled missing popularity values

---

# 5. Feature Engineering

## Definition

Creating useful features that improve model performance.

## Examples

Original Feature:

Date of Birth

Engineered Features:

* Age
* Age Group

## Purpose

Help the model learn important patterns.

---

# 6. Model Training

## Definition

The model learns patterns from training data.

## Examples

Regression:

* Linear Regression

Clustering:

* K-Means

Deep Learning:

* CNN

Reinforcement Learning:

* Q-Learning

## Output

A trained model.

---

# 7. Model Evaluation

## Definition

Measure how well the model performs on unseen data.

## Common Metrics

### Regression

* MAE
* MSE
* RMSE
* R² Score

### Classification

* Accuracy
* Precision
* Recall
* F1 Score

### Clustering

* Silhouette Score
* WCSS

---

# 8. Model Deployment

## Definition

Making the trained model available for real-world use.

## Examples

* Website
* Mobile App
* API
* Cloud Service

## Example

Handwritten Digit Recognition Web App

User uploads a digit image

↓

Model predicts the digit

↓

Prediction displayed

---

# 9. Model Monitoring

## Definition

Tracking model performance after deployment.

## Why?

Real-world data changes over time.

A model that performs well today may become less accurate later.

## Things to Monitor

* Accuracy
* Latency
* User feedback
* Data drift

---

# 10. Model Retraining

## Definition

Updating the model using new data.

## Purpose

Improve performance and adapt to changing patterns.

## Example

Retraining a recommendation system with newly released movies.

---

# 11. Continuous Improvement

## Definition

Machine learning is an iterative process.

Teams continuously:

* Collect new data
* Improve features
* Tune hyperparameters
* Deploy better models

This cycle repeats throughout the model's life.

